<mi>&#916;</mi><mi>E</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>M</mi><mi>c</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>06</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>19</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>67</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>27</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>8</mn></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>17</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (26 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39022,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mi>eV</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2815</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>eV</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>331</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>eV</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>27</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>eV</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>E</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>r</mi></mfrac><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>m</mi></mrow></mfrac></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>E</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><mi>m</mi></math>. Ionization potential <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mfenced><msub><mtext>Mass</mtext><mi>&#956;</mi></msub></mfenced><mi>eV</mi></mrow><mfenced><msub><mtext>Mass</mtext><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></msub></mfenced></mfrac></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>207</mn><mi>eV</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2815</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>eV</mi></math>.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (18 Mar Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":38948,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["$\\frac{3}{2}$","$\\frac{4}{9}$","$\\frac{9}{4}$","$\\frac{2}{3}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\mathrm{r}=\\mathrm{r} \\cdot \\frac{\\mathrm{n}^2}{2}$<br/>for $\\mathrm{Li}^{2+}$<br/>$r_5=r \\cdot \\frac{25}{3}$<br/>for $\\mathrm{He}^{+}$<br/>$\\begin{aligned}<br/>& \\mathrm{r}_5=\\mathrm{r} \\cdot \\frac{25}{2} \\\\\n& \\therefore \\frac{\\mathrm{r}_{\\mathrm{Li}^{2+}}}{\\mathrm{r}_{\\mathrm{He}^{+}}}=\\frac{2}{3}<br/>\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (4 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":38977,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p style=\"text-align: justify;\">For minimum potential difference, electron has to make transition from <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></math> to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></math>  state but first electron has to reach to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></math> state from ground state. So, energy of bombarding electron should be equal to energy difference of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>3</mn></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>n</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math> state.</p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>Δ</mi><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\"><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msup><mn>3</mn><mn>2</mn></msup></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mi>e</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>e</mi><mi>V</mi></math></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>8</mn></mrow><mn>9</mn></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>V</mi></math></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>12</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>09</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mo>≈</mo><mn>12</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math></p><p style=\"text-align: justify;\">So, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>α</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>121</mn></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (29 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":38978,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/a9134e88-3350-4cce-87c0-3c2098c5ec83.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 135px;\"/></p><p>According to the above diagram, the difference in energy between the two states is given by</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable columnalign=\"right center left\" columnspacing=\"0px\"><mtr><mtd><mi>ΔE</mi></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo> </mo><mi>eV</mi><mo>-</mo><mfenced><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>13</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo> </mo><mi>eV</mi></mrow></mfenced></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mn>10</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo> </mo><mi>eV</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p><p>The formula to calculate the recoil speed is given by</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>∆</mo><mi>E</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>m</mi><mi>c</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo> </mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mfenced><mn>1</mn></mfenced></math></p><p>From equation (1), it follows that</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable columnalign=\"right center left\" columnspacing=\"0px\"><mtr><mtd><mi>v</mi></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mfrac><mrow><mn>10</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo> </mo><mi>eV</mi><mo>×</mo><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>19</mn></mrow></msup><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo> </mo><mi>eV</mi></mrow></mfrac></mstyle></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>27</mn></mrow></msup><mo> </mo><mi>kg</mi><mo>×</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>8</mn></msup><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo> </mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo> </mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mfrac><mn>17</mn><mn>5</mn></mfrac><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo> </mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p><p>Therefore, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>17</mn></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (29 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":38967,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["$\\frac{h}{\\pi}$","$\\frac{h}{2 \\pi}$","$8 \\frac{h}{\\pi}$","$2 \\frac{h}{\\pi}$"],"answer":3,"solution":"Moment of momentum is $\\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{r}} \\times \\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{P}}$\n$\\begin{aligned}\n& \\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{L}}=\\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{r}} \\times \\mathrm{m} \\overrightarrow{\\mathrm{v}} \\\\\n& \\mathrm{L}=\\mathrm{mvr}=\\frac{\\mathrm{nh}}{2 \\pi}=\\frac{4 \\mathrm{~h}}{2 \\pi}=\\frac{2 \\mathrm{~h}}{\\pi}\n\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (04 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":38952,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["(B), (D) only","(A), (B) only","(A), (D) only","(A), (C) only"],"answer":1,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} & \\mathrm{E} \\propto \\frac{\\mathrm{Z}}{\\mathrm{n}^2} \\\\ & \\mathrm{Z}_{\\mathrm{H}}=1 \\quad \\mathrm{Z}_{\\mathrm{He}^{+}}=2 \\quad \\mathrm{Z}_{\\mathrm{Li}^{+2}}=3\\end{aligned}$<br/>$\\begin{aligned} & 1^{\\text {st }} \\text { excited state } \\Rightarrow \\mathrm{n}=2 \\\\ & 2^{\\text {nd }} \\text { excited state } \\Rightarrow \\mathrm{n}=3\\end{aligned}$<br/>From the given statements only A \\& B are correct.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (2 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":38991,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The formula to calculate the radius of Lithium-ion is given by</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>R</mi><mi>Li</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>R</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>Z</mi></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>.</mo><mo>(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>)</mo></math></p><p>Substitute the values of the known parameters into equation (1) to calculate the required radius of the ion.</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtable columnalign=\"right center left\" columnspacing=\"0px\"><mtr><mtd><msub><mi>R</mi><mrow><mi>L</mi><mi>i</mi></mrow></msub></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>51</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>25</mn></mrow><mn>3</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd></mtd><mtd><mo>=</mo></mtd><mtd><mn>425</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>12</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mtd></mtr></mtable></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (06 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39059,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["20.4 eV","10.2 eV","12.1 eV","16.8 eV"],"answer":0,"solution":"Let velocity before collision v from momentum conservation <math> <mi>m</mi><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><mrow><mo>(</mo> <mrow> <mi>m</mi><mo>+</mo><mi>m</mi></mrow> <mo>)</mo></mrow><msup> <mi>v</mi> <mn>1</mn> </msup> </math><br /><br /><math> <msup> <mi>v</mi> <mn>1</mn> </msup> <mo>=</mo><mfrac> <mi>v</mi> <mn>2</mn> </mfrac> </math><br /><br />Loss in K.E. <math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mi>m</mi><msup><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>m</mi></mrow></mfenced><msup><mrow><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math><br /><br /><math><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfrac><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mi>m</mi><msup><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math><br /><br />K.E. lost is used to jump from <math><msup><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>s</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></msup></math> orbit to <math><msup><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi><mi>d</mi></mrow></msup></math> orbit <math><mo>∆</mo><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mi>K</mi><mo>.</mo><mi>E</mi><mo>.</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>10.2</mn><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>V</mi></math><br /><br /><math><mo>⇒</mo><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn></mrow></mfrac><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mi>m</mi><msup><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>10.2</mn></math><br /><br /><math><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mi>m</mi><msup><mrow><mi>v</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>×</mo><mn>10.2</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>20.4</mn><mi>&nbsp;</mi><mi>e</mi><mi>V</mi></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2016 (10 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":39090,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["$10.2 \\mathrm{eV}$","$0 \\mathrm{eV}$","$3.4 \\mathrm{eV}$","$6.8 \\mathrm{eV}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"$E_n=-\\frac{13.6}{n^2} \\Rightarrow E_2=-\\frac{13.6}{2^2}=3.4 \\mathrm{eV}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2002","image":null},{"id":38936,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["$27$ and $20$","$3$ and $16$","$5$ and $36$","$20$ and $27$"],"answer":3,"solution":"The momentum of a photon is given by $p = \\dfrac{h}{\\lambda}$.<br><br>From Rydberg's formula, the wave number is $\\dfrac{1}{\\lambda} = R \\left( \\dfrac{1}{n_1^2} - \\dfrac{1}{n_2^2} \\right)$.<br><br>For the first line of the Balmer series, the transition is from $n_2 = 3$ to $n_1 = 2$.<br><br>$p_1 = \\dfrac{h}{\\lambda_1} = hR \\left( \\dfrac{1}{2^2} - \\dfrac{1}{3^2} \\right) = hR \\left( \\dfrac{1}{4} - \\dfrac{1}{9} \\right) = \\dfrac{5hR}{36}$<br><br>For the second line of the Balmer series, the transition is from $n_2 = 4$ to $n_1 = 2$.<br><br>$p_2 = \\dfrac{h}{\\lambda_2} = hR \\left( \\dfrac{1}{2^2} - \\dfrac{1}{4^2} \\right) = hR \\left( \\dfrac{1}{4} - \\dfrac{1}{16} \\right) = \\dfrac{3hR}{16}$<br><br>The ratio of the momenta is:<br><br>$\\dfrac{p_1}{p_2} = \\dfrac{\\dfrac{5hR}{36}}{\\dfrac{3hR}{16}} = \\dfrac{5}{36} \\times \\dfrac{16}{3} = \\dfrac{20}{27}$<br><br>Comparing with $\\dfrac{\\alpha}{\\beta}$, the possible values are $\\alpha = 20$ and $\\beta = 27$.<br><br>Answer: $20$ and $27$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (06 April Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":38961,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} & 10.2 \\mathrm{eV}=\\frac{\\mathrm{hc}}{\\lambda} \\\\ & \\lambda=\\frac{1245 \\mathrm{eV}-\\mathrm{nm}}{10.2 \\mathrm{eV}}=122.06 \\mathrm{~nm}\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (06 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":39078,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["$2$","$3$","$5$","$6$"],"answer":3,"solution":"Number of spectral lines from a state $\\mathrm{n}$ to ground state is\n$=\\frac{n(n-1)}{2}=6.$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (Offline)","image":null},{"id":39077,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["$D$","$B$","$C$","$A$"],"answer":2,"solution":"As $\\alpha$-particles are doubly ionised helium $\\mathrm{He}^{++}$i.e. Positively charged and nucleus is also positively charged and we know that like charges repel each other.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (07 May Online)","image":null},{"id":38941,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["8 and 10","9 and 8","10 and 12","6 and 5"],"answer":3,"solution":"For hydrogen-like atoms:<br>$V \\propto \\frac{Z}{n}$ and $r \\propto \\frac{n^2}{Z}$<br>Thus $r \\propto \\frac{n}{V}$<br>Since the radii are nearly the same:<br>$\\frac{n_1}{V_1} = \\frac{n_2}{V_2}$<br>$\\frac{n_1}{n_2} = \\frac{V_1}{V_2} = \\frac{3 \\times 10^5}{2.5 \\times 10^5} = \\frac{6}{5}$<br>Possible order of energy states is 6 and 5.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (24 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39051,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["$\\lambda_{\\mathrm{CM}}=\\lambda_1=\\lambda_2$","$\\frac{1}{\\lambda_1}=\\frac{1}{\\lambda_1}+\\frac{1}{\\lambda_2}$","$\\lambda_{C M}=\\frac{2 \\lambda_1 \\lambda_2}{\\sqrt{\\lambda_1^2+\\lambda_2^2}}$","$\\lambda_{C M}=\\left(\\frac{\\lambda_1+\\lambda_2}{2}\\right)$"],"answer":2,"solution":"Momentum (p) of each electron $\\frac{\\mathrm{h}}{\\lambda_1} \\hat{\\mathrm{i}}$ and $\\frac{\\mathrm{h}}{\\lambda_2} \\hat{\\mathrm{j}}$\nVelocity of centre of mass\n$$\n\\mathrm{V}_{\\mathrm{cm}}=\\frac{\\mathrm{h}}{2 \\mathrm{~m} \\lambda_1} \\hat{\\mathrm{i}}+\\frac{\\mathrm{h}}{2 \\mathrm{~m} \\lambda_2} \\hat{\\mathrm{j}} \\quad(\\because \\mathrm{p}=\\mathrm{mv})\n$$\nVelocity of 1 st particle about centre of mass\n$$\nV_{1 \\mathrm{~cm}}=\\frac{\\mathrm{h}}{2 \\mathrm{~m} \\lambda_1} \\hat{\\mathrm{i}}-\\frac{\\mathrm{h}}{2 \\mathrm{~m} \\lambda_2} \\hat{\\mathrm{j}}\n$$\n$\\lambda_{\\mathrm{cm}}=\\frac{\\mathrm{h}}{\\sqrt{\\frac{\\mathrm{h}^2}{4 \\lambda_1^2}+\\frac{\\mathrm{h}^2}{4 \\lambda_2^2}}}=\\frac{2 \\lambda_1 \\lambda_2}{\\sqrt{\\lambda_1^2+\\lambda_2^2}} \\quad\\left(\\because \\lambda=\\frac{\\mathrm{h}}{\\mathrm{p}}\\right)$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr Shift 1 Online)","image":null},{"id":38946,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["4","2","1","3"],"answer":3,"solution":"$\\Delta \\mathrm{E}=13.6 \\mathrm{z}^2\\left[\\frac{1}{\\mathrm{n}_1^2}-\\frac{1}{\\mathrm{n}_2^2}\\right]$<br/>$(13.6) \\mathrm{z}^2\\left[\\frac{1}{1}-\\frac{1}{9}\\right]=108.8$<br/>$\\frac{(13.6)(8)}{9}\\left(z^2\\right)=108.8$<br/>$\\mathrm{z}=3$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2025 (7 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":38993,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>In <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi><mo>,</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Z</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>17</mn></math>&nbsp;and have equal numbers of protons and neutrons i.e. nucleons<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>17</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>34</mn></math></p><p>So, for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi></math>,&nbsp;</p><p>Total binding energy&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><msub><mi>E</mi><mi>A</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>34</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>40</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>MeV</mi></math></p><p>Another nucleus&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi></math> mass number&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>26</mn></math></p><p>So, total binding energy of&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi></math>&nbsp;is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><msub><mi>E</mi><mi>B</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>26</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>MeV</mi></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>46</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>MeV</mi></math></p><p>Difference of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>B</mi><msub><mi>E</mi><mi>B</mi></msub><mo>-</mo><mi>B</mi><msub><mi>E</mi><mi>A</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>MeV</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (01 Feb Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":38962,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["$4: 1$","$1: 4$","$2: 1$","$1: 2$"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/4ela7w8dB5SOEx_kJClfzBLdiMqGntpfAMZuEp4gTH4.original.fullsize.png\"><br />$\\begin{aligned} & \\frac{1}{\\lambda}=\\mathrm{Rz}^2\\left(\\frac{1}{\\mathrm{n}_1^2}-\\frac{1}{\\mathrm{n}_2^2}\\right) \\\\ & \\frac{\\frac{1}{\\lambda_{\\mathrm{L}}}=\\mathrm{Rz}^2\\left(\\frac{1}{1^2}\\right)}{\\frac{1}{\\lambda_{\\mathrm{B}}}=\\mathrm{Rz}^2\\left(\\frac{1}{2^2}\\right)} \\\\ & \\frac{\\lambda_{\\mathrm{B}}}{\\lambda_{\\mathrm{L}}}=4: 1\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (06 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":38982,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The energy of a photon is given by&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>h</mi><mi>c</mi></mrow><mi>&#955;</mi></mfrac></math>.</p><p>It is given that&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>500</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>nm</mi></math>,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>600</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>nm</mi></math>.</p><p>The net energy absorbed is&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#916;</mi><mi>E</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>h</mi><mi>c</mi></mrow><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>h</mi><mi>c</mi></mrow><msub><mi>&#955;</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>h</mi><mi>c</mi></mrow><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn></mrow></msup></mfrac><mo>(</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>500</mn></mfrac><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>600</mn></mfrac><mo>)</mo></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>34</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>8</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>500</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>600</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>9</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow><mn>30</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>19</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>eV</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>19</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">J</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>30</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn></mrow></mfrac><mi>e</mi><mi>V</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>4125</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>eV</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (13 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":38998,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>7</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>8</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<p>For hydrogen like atom, the velocity of electron in&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mi>n</mi><mrow><mi>t</mi><mi>h</mi></mrow></msup></math>&nbsp;orbit is given by</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mi>z</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><msup><mi>e</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><msub><mi>&#949;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>h</mi><mi>n</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><mi>v</mi><mo>&#8733;</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>n</mi></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><msub><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>n</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>3</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup></mrow><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>3</mn><mn>7</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>v</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>6</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (30 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":39069,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["$n^2$","$n$","$n^{1 / 2}$","$n^{1 / 4}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"According to the question,\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& 2 \\pi \\mathrm{r}=\\mathrm{n} \\lambda=\\frac{\\mathrm{nh}}{\\mathrm{p}}=\\frac{\\mathrm{nh}}{\\mathrm{mv}} \\\\\n& \\text { or } \\mathrm{mvr}=\\frac{\\mathrm{nh}}{2 \\pi} \\text { or } \\mathrm{mv}=\\frac{\\mathrm{nh}}{2 \\pi \\mathrm{r}} \\\\\n& \\mathrm{F}=\\mathrm{qv}_{\\mathrm{B}}=\\frac{\\mathrm{mv}^2}{\\mathrm{r}} \\\\\n& \\text { or, } \\mathrm{q}_{\\mathrm{B}}=\\frac{\\mathrm{mv}}{\\mathrm{r}}=\\frac{\\mathrm{nh}}{2 \\pi \\mathrm{r} \\cdot \\mathrm{r}} \\\\\n& \\text { or, } \\mathrm{r}^2=\\frac{\\mathrm{nh}}{2 \\pi \\mathrm{qB}} \\\\\n& \\text { or, } \\mathrm{r}=\\sqrt{\\frac{\\mathrm{nh}}{2 \\pi \\mathrm{qB}}} \\\\\n& \\text { i.e., } \\mathrm{r} \\propto \\mathrm{n}^{1 / 2}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (22 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":39071,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["<math> <mrow> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> <mrow> <msup> <mtext>n</mtext> <mrow> <mn>3</mn> <mo>/</mo> <mn>2</mn> </mrow> </msup> </mrow> </mfrac> </mrow> </math>","<math> <mrow> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> <mrow> <msup> <mtext>n</mtext> <mn>3</mn> </msup> </mrow> </mfrac> </mrow> </math>","<math> <mrow> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> <mrow> <mtext>n</mtext> </mrow> </mfrac> </mrow> </math>","<math> <mrow> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> <mrow> <mrow> <msup> <mtext>n</mtext> <mn>2</mn> </msup> </mrow> </mrow> </mfrac> </mrow> </math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<math> <mrow> <mo>&#916;</mo> <mtext>E</mtext> <mo>=</mo> <mtext>h</mtext> <mi>&#957;</mi> </mrow> </math><br /><math> <mrow> <mi>&#957;</mi> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mo>&#916;</mo> <mtext>E</mtext> </mrow> <mrow> <mtext>h</mtext> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>=</mo> <mtext>k</mtext> <mfenced close=\"]\" open=\"[\" separators=\",\"> <mrow> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> <mrow> <msup> <mrow> <mfenced close=\")\" open=\"(\" separators=\",\"> <mrow> <mtext>n</mtext> <mo>-</mo> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> </mfenced> </mrow> <mn>2</mn> </msup> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>-</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> <mrow> <msup> <mtext>n</mtext> <mn>2</mn> </msup> </mrow> </mfrac> </mrow> </mfenced> <mo>=</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mtext>k</mtext> <mn>2</mn> <mtext>n</mtext> </mrow> <mrow> <msup> <mtext>n</mtext> <mn>2</mn> </msup> <msup> <mrow> <mfenced close=\")\" open=\"(\" separators=\",\"> <mrow> <mtext>n</mtext> <mo>-</mo> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> </mfenced> </mrow> <mn>2</mn> </msup> </mrow> </mfrac> </mrow> </math><br /><br /><math> <mrow> <mo>&#8776;</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>2</mn> <mtext>k</mtext> </mrow> <mrow> <msup> <mtext>n</mtext> <mn>3</mn> </msup> </mrow> </mfrac> <mo>&#8733;</mo> <mfrac> <mrow> <mn>1</mn> </mrow> <mrow> <msup> <mtext>n</mtext> <mn>3</mn> </msup> </mrow> </mfrac> </mrow> </math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2013 (07 Apr)","image":null},{"id":39081,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Atomic Physics","question":"","options":["$2 \\rightarrow 1$","$3 \\rightarrow 2$","$4 \\rightarrow 2$","$5 \\rightarrow 4$"],"answer":3,"solution":"IR corresponds to least value of $\\left(\\frac{1}{n_1^2}-\\frac{1}{n_2^2}\\right)$\ni.e. from Paschen, Bracket and Pfund series. Thus the transition corresponds to $5 \\rightarrow 3$.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2009","image":null}]